reviews.title: Oven Roasted Brussel Sprouts
reviews.review_text: Excellent produce-fresh and clean-already halved and ready to cook. I love to rub them in olive oil and season with salt and pepper- and put oil sprayed parchment paper on a sheet pan- and add shredded parmesan -put the seasoned cut brussel sprouts on the parmesan -cut side down. roast in 350 degree over for about 35 -45 minutes until browned -they are always a big hit and a great side dish to any dinner.

reviews.title: Dirty, dried out, and full of cabbage worms
reviews.review_text: Also, they were poorly cut. Most of the bag was unusable. I was able to salvage one small serving's worth by soaking in salt water (makes the cabbage worms rise to the top and the dirt fall to the bottom), removing several holey, dried-out leaves, rinsing several more times, and re-trimming the remainders. Avoiding all of which is the whole reason for buying pre-cut in the first place! At least half didn't even get into the bath though. They were simply out of the question. Would never buy again.

reviews.title: Always moldy no matter what
reviews.review_text: theres a clear problem with this product. i frequently get moldy sprouts. the cut side should be bright yellow/white/green. its always brown and fuzzy. even prior to expiration date. Theres obviously an issue with cutting them. The blade isnt sanitary or something they are doing after cutting isnt sanitary. Avoid these. Cutting to the good part isnt safe with mold due to spores you wont see. the specks and fuzzy appearance are a dead giveaway. Its something they are doing to all of them though because in the zoomed out pics you can see every single one is dark brown and fuzzy only on the cut side.

reviews.title: So convenient and no waste
reviews.review_text: I noticed these had a low rating and I don't know why. The only downside to these are that they are more expensive than I think they should be. But it's due to the extra processing to make these so convenient that you don't have to do any prep work. Zero prep work! I lose so many leaves from whole Brussels sprouts that the wasted scrap is a considerable amount and I have never had to throw away any leaves from these ready to cook sprouts. You can microwave them in the bag it comes in. But we roast it in the oven coated with olive oil, garlic salt and pepper. You can add dried cranberries and chopped pecans or walnuts in the final 8 minutes to make it really special. One of my kids would not eat Brussels sprouts if not for these. He would never pick through each and pull off half the leaves and chop off the stems. But he eats them frequently because of the convenience. Try these! But beware. You may never buy whole sprouts again.
